05620nam a22006615i 9780773572744DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20052005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735727447 a10.1515/97807735727442doi  a(DE-B1597)657420  a(OCoLC)243600850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNK1413.A1bM34 2005eb 7aDES0000002bisacsh04a745/.0971/090461 aElder, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMade in Canada :bCraft and Design in the Sixties /cAlan Elder. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (144 p.) :b32 colour photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tForeword Design Exchange -- tForeword Canadian Museum of Civilization -- tCanada in the Sixties - "It can do almost anything" -- tDesigning a Modern Nation -- tWhen "la Dolce Vita" Met "True Canadianism": Canadian Airports in the Sixties -- t"Instant World": Canada and Space-Age Design in the Sixties -- tA Flag for Canada -- tCanada Welcomes the World -- tExcellence, Inventiveness, and Variety: Canadian Fine Crafts at Expo 67 -- tHabitat '67: View from the Inside -- tSame Decade, Different Styles -- tCapsules: Plastic and Utopia -- tDeign to Be Modern: Canada's Taste for Scandinavian Design in the Sixties -- tWhen Counterculture Went Mainstream -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe red maple leaf is the quintessential symbol of Canada and the flag that popularized it throughout the world was designed in the 1960s as a result of government legislation aimed at creating a vital, new Canadian national identity through objects, events, and building projects. Made in Canada looks at the development of Canadian craft, design, and culture through ambitious government programs meant to reinforce the country's identity as a modern, sophisticated, and autonomous nation. As well, it documents the demise of a singular notion of modern life and its replacement with a focus on personal identity and consumerism. Changes in the 1960s included the building of modern airports, first space satellite, and new national symbols such as the maple leaf flag. Canadians embraced this heightened sense of individuality and demanded products that were equally individual. As a result pop culture objects sat on cool furniture influenced by Scandinavian modernism while handmade crafts reflected a growing concern with environmental issues. Expo 67 was the turning point - one final expression of optimism before Canada was rocked by social change and varied struggles for identity. Made in Canada examines national dreams and expressions of individuality in thoughtful and illuminating essays. Contributors include Sandra Alfoldy (NSCAD University), Paul Bourassa (Musée des beaux-arts de Québec), Brent Cordner (designer and educator, Toronto), Douglas Coupland (artist and author, Vancouver), Bernard Flaman (Government of Saskatchewan), Rachel Gotlieb (freelance curator and writer, Toronto), Michael Large (Sheridan College Institute of Technology and Advanced Learning), and Michael Prokopow (Design Exchange).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDesignxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDesignzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHandicraftxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHandicraftzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNineteen sixties. 7aDESIGN / General.2bisacsh1 aAlfoldy, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourassa, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordner, Brent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/